  pages = {294--305},
  number = {3},
  month = mar,
  abstract = {Genome-wide association studies are designed to discover SNPs that
	are associated with a complex trait. Employing strict significance
	thresholds when testing individual SNPs avoids false positives at
	the expense of increasing false negatives. Recently, we developed
	a method for quantitative traits that estimates the variation accounted
	for when fitting all SNPs simultaneously. Here we develop this method
	further for case-control studies. We use a linear mixed model for
	analysis of binary traits and transform the estimates to a liability
	scale by adjusting both for scale and for ascertainment of the case
	samples. We show by theory and simulation that the method is unbiased.
